05696nam a22008775i 9780812291728DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979741432  a97808122917287 a10.9783/97808122917282doi  a(DE-B1597)452742  a(OCoLC)918594820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a304.8 45223  aLB 560002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90572:7721 aAlbahari, Maurizio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrimes of Peace :bMediterranean Migrations at the World's Deadliest Border /cMaurizio Albahari. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPART I. JOURNEYS -- tIntroduction: On the Threshold of Liberty -- tChapter 1. Genealogies of Care and Confinement -- tChapter 2. Genealogies of Rescue and Pushbacks -- tPART II. MIDDLE WORLDS -- tChapter 3. Sovereignty as Salvation: Moral States -- tChapter 4. Sovereignty as Preemption: Undocumented States -- tPART III. BORDERS ADRIFT -- tChapter 5. Spring Uprisings, Fall Drownings -- tChapter 6. Public Aesthetics Amid Seas -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the world's hotly contested, obsessively controlled, and often dangerous borders, none is deadlier than the Mediterranean Sea. Since 2000, at least 25,000 people have lost their lives attempting to reach Italy and the rest of Europe, most by drowning in the Mediterranean. Every day, unauthorized migrants and refugees bound for Europe put their lives in the hands of maritime smugglers, while fishermen, diplomats, priests, bureaucrats, armed forces sailors, and hesitant bystanders waver between indifference and intervention—with harrowing results.In Crimes of Peace, Maurizio Albahari investigates why the Mediterranean Sea is the world's deadliest border, and what alternatives could improve this state of affairs. He also examines the dismal conditions of migrants in transit and the institutional framework in which they move or are physically confined. Drawing on his intimate knowledge of places, people, and European politics, Albahari supplements fieldwork in coastal southern Italy and neighboring Mediterranean locales with a meticulous documentary investigation, transforming abstract statistics into names and narratives that place the responsibility for the Mediterranean migration crisis in the very heart of liberal democracy. Global fault lines are scrutinized: between Europe, Africa, and the Middle East; military and humanitarian governance; detention and hospitality; transnational crime and statecraft; the universal law of the sea and the thresholds of a globalized yet parochial world. Crimes of Peace illuminates crucial questions of sovereignty and rights: for migrants trying to enter Europe along the Mediterranean shore, the answers are a matter of life or death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aImmigrantsxMortalityzMediterranean RegionxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxMortalityzMediterranean RegionxHistoryy21st century. 0aImmigrants; Mortality; Mediterranean Region; History, 20th century. 0aImmigrants; Mortality; Mediterranean Region; History, 21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle 